1
00:00:01,625 --> 00:00:05,688
The Yaoshima Group...

2
00:00:06,854 --> 00:00:08,844
will disband the Dreams.

3
00:00:08,844 --> 00:00:10,626
What?

4
00:00:10,626 --> 00:00:14,575
Why are the stars
of the Stove League disbanding?

5
00:00:14,575 --> 00:00:19,077
For years, the Dreams
have disappointed their fans.

6
00:00:19,077 --> 00:00:22,788
I am merely taking accountability
as the owner representative.

7
00:00:22,788 --> 00:00:24,767
They tied against the Vikings
in a practice game.

8
00:00:24,767 --> 00:00:27,778
They're also performing well
in the ongoing league.

9
00:00:27,778 --> 00:00:30,651
Everyone believes this is their year.

10
00:00:30,651 --> 00:00:35,094
No, no, you overestimate their potential.

11
00:00:35,094 --> 00:00:37,194
This is nothing new.

12
00:00:37,194 --> 00:00:40,574
Weak teams shine during the Stove League,

13
00:00:40,574 --> 00:00:43,439
yet ultimately disappoint their fans.

14
00:00:43,439 --> 00:00:45,353
There must be another reason.

15
00:00:45,353 --> 00:00:46,662
Tell us the truth!

16
00:00:46,662 --> 00:00:49,561
- Mr. Negishi, please.
- Please answer us.

17
00:00:52,192 --> 00:00:55,638
That is all I have to say on the matter.

18
00:01:20,633 --> 00:01:23,678
You look familiar...

19
00:01:23,678 --> 00:01:25,421
Who are you again?

20
00:01:25,421 --> 00:01:26,531
Forget him.

21
00:01:26,531 --> 00:01:27,966
Out of the way.

22
00:01:28,469 --> 00:01:30,388
My name is Sakurazaki.

23
00:01:31,144 --> 00:01:32,766
Sakurazaki?

24
00:01:35,468 --> 00:01:37,145
I remember now.

25
00:01:37,145 --> 00:01:40,234
I hear you're quite the capable GM.

26
00:01:40,234 --> 00:01:43,121
Isami seems to have
benefited greatly from you.

27
00:01:44,367 --> 00:01:47,364
Sir. If you give me the proper time,

28
00:01:49,018 --> 00:01:51,045
I will sell the Dreams.

29
00:01:51,045 --> 00:01:53,840
Oh? I'm intrigued.

30
00:01:53,840 --> 00:01:55,489
What?

31
00:01:55,489 --> 00:01:57,588
Who do you think you are?

32
00:01:57,588 --> 00:01:59,290
Stay!

33
00:01:59,290 --> 00:02:01,361
Stay there!

34
00:02:02,933 --> 00:02:04,547
Here?

35
00:02:08,551 --> 00:02:10,261
What do you want?

36
00:02:10,918 --> 00:02:13,083
Disbanding a baseball team is unprecedented.

37
00:02:13,083 --> 00:02:16,434
It would reflect negatively
on the Yaoshima Group.

38
00:02:17,037 --> 00:02:19,300
It's not a sound plan.

39
00:02:19,300 --> 00:02:23,722
Sell the team, and you make a profit.
Two birds, one stone.

40
00:02:23,722 --> 00:02:26,874
Your idea is certainly a good one.

41
00:02:26,874 --> 00:02:30,620
But I've already tried selling the team.

42
00:02:30,620 --> 00:02:35,391
Please allow me to handle it.

43
00:02:51,748 --> 00:02:53,922
That's a good look you got there.

44
00:02:55,250 --> 00:03:00,017
Do you know what you have, that I don't?

45
00:03:02,734 --> 00:03:04,115
No.

46
00:03:05,476 --> 00:03:06,716
I do not.

47
00:03:06,716 --> 00:03:08,258
It's time.

48
00:03:11,497 --> 00:03:15,985
Unlike you, my time here runs short.

49
00:03:17,130 --> 00:03:18,468
Sir, the team sells
for at least 10 billion...

50
00:03:18,468 --> 00:03:20,123
Shut up!

51
00:03:23,257 --> 00:03:26,354
Call me if you need a job.

52
00:03:36,169 --> 00:03:39,800
You got the looks, I'll give you that.

53
00:04:21,928 --> 00:04:23,978
So it's begun.

54
00:04:51,599 --> 00:04:54,831
The Dreams aren't disbanded yet!

55
00:04:54,831 --> 00:04:57,111
Please don't call me again.

56
00:05:04,677 --> 00:05:06,294
Kijima.

57
00:05:06,919 --> 00:05:08,687
Everyone's on edge.

58
00:05:08,687 --> 00:05:11,076
They need your words of encouragement.

59
00:05:15,681 --> 00:05:17,082
Right.

60
00:05:24,819 --> 00:05:27,125
I get you're all anxious.

61
00:05:28,655 --> 00:05:30,928
If it comes down to it, transfer elsewhere.

62
00:05:32,263 --> 00:05:34,826
I promise a team will take you in.

63
00:05:36,366 --> 00:05:38,052
So calm those nerves.

64
00:05:39,799 --> 00:05:42,684
Let's trust our staff and GM.

65
00:05:42,684 --> 00:05:45,117
We have a preseason game to focus on.

66
00:05:46,039 --> 00:05:47,583
Got that?

67
00:05:47,583 --> 00:05:49,088
Yes, sir!

68
00:05:49,592 --> 00:05:51,891
Alright, that's it for today's practice.

69
00:05:51,891 --> 00:05:53,864
- Okay.
- Who's getting drinks with me?

70
00:05:53,864 --> 00:05:56,022
- I am!
- Yeah!

71
00:06:11,893 --> 00:06:13,729
Welcome.

72
00:06:21,548 --> 00:06:23,903
- I'll take what he's having.
- Certainly.

73
00:06:24,917 --> 00:06:27,288
- And a side dish, please.
- Of course.

74
00:06:32,159 --> 00:06:35,004
What do you want?

75
00:06:35,004 --> 00:06:37,159
I'm only here as a customer.

76
00:06:38,704 --> 00:06:42,950
You're still so arrogant.

77
00:06:43,470 --> 00:06:44,881
But no matter.

78
00:06:44,881 --> 00:06:47,756
You don't report to me anymore.

79
00:06:48,673 --> 00:06:53,958
It's refreshing to part ways
with someone who sold their soul.

80
00:06:57,742 --> 00:07:00,973
That's a terrible thing to say.

81
00:07:00,973 --> 00:07:07,816
All office workers in the world
sell their souls to work.

82
00:07:10,860 --> 00:07:14,673
Because you live a prideful life,

83
00:07:14,673 --> 00:07:17,107
your subordinates suffer.

84
00:07:23,542 --> 00:07:26,250
The team was disbanded.

85
00:07:26,250 --> 00:07:31,024
Must be quite the inconvenience
for both players and staff alike.

86
00:07:32,600 --> 00:07:37,640
In the past, I may have felt responsible.

87
00:07:38,825 --> 00:07:40,737
But not anymore.

88
00:07:43,620 --> 00:07:46,728
I will continue to stand by my beliefs,

89
00:07:46,728 --> 00:07:49,001
for the sake of those who believe in me.

90
00:07:51,290 --> 00:07:54,034
Say what you will.

91
00:07:54,034 --> 00:07:56,812
But nothing will change.

92
00:07:56,812 --> 00:08:00,531
Things can change. And I'm certain they will.

93
00:08:03,893 --> 00:08:10,344
All the staff who know you
agree that you're an excellent businessman.

94
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:17,250
In which case,
you should prioritize profit above all else.

95
00:08:21,462 --> 00:08:25,598
You truly think you can sell a baseball team?

96
00:08:29,390 --> 00:08:32,152
I failed to do so, time and time again.

97
00:08:33,621 --> 00:08:35,729
I can do it.

98
00:08:37,310 --> 00:08:39,363
In this region,

99
00:08:39,363 --> 00:08:43,725
there are no other corporations
who can run the Dreams.

100
00:08:43,725 --> 00:08:45,957
Leave that to me.

101
00:08:49,499 --> 00:08:53,272
If we bring in 10 billion yen,
the CEO will surely be pleased.

102
00:08:54,593 --> 00:08:56,467
And if I refuse?

103
00:09:00,005 --> 00:09:05,007
I heard your father truly loved the Dreams.

104
00:09:05,007 --> 00:09:06,911
So what?

105
00:09:07,633 --> 00:09:09,260
He was a wonderful team president.

106
00:09:09,260 --> 00:09:11,024
Enough.

107
00:09:11,926 --> 00:09:16,326
To the fans, the Dreams
aren't just a baseball team.

108
00:09:16,326 --> 00:09:18,606
They're a part of their lives.

109
00:09:20,019 --> 00:09:22,218
You should know how that feels.

110
00:09:25,748 --> 00:09:28,140
The CEO wouldn't agree.

111
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:34,020
Give me one week.

112
00:09:37,195 --> 00:09:39,019
You don't have the time.

113
00:09:52,634 --> 00:09:56,485
You need food in your stomach.
Or you'll fall sick.

114
00:10:33,779 --> 00:10:37,751
The GM intends to find a buyer
after getting Yaoshima's consent.

115
00:10:37,751 --> 00:10:40,190
Yaoshima is indifferent to the team.

116
00:10:40,190 --> 00:10:42,630
But that could go either way for us.

117
00:10:42,630 --> 00:10:44,543
I just hope we'll hear good news.

118
00:10:44,543 --> 00:10:47,976
Yikes, I'm shaking in my boots.

119
00:10:47,976 --> 00:10:48,777
Ouch!

120
00:10:48,777 --> 00:10:52,152
Can you pipe down?
Whining won't get us anywhere.

121
00:10:52,152 --> 00:10:55,360
That's harsh!

122
00:10:55,360 --> 00:10:57,849
You're way too on edge, Prez.

123
00:10:57,849 --> 00:10:58,908
- Relax.
- Shut up.

124
00:10:58,908 --> 00:11:00,437
Relax, okay?

125
00:11:02,650 --> 00:11:03,938
Excuse me for a moment.

126
00:11:03,938 --> 00:11:05,339
Huh?

127
00:11:05,339 --> 00:11:07,493
We're in a meeting.

128
00:11:08,793 --> 00:11:10,403
I have to take this.

129
00:11:10,403 --> 00:11:12,029
Huh? No, wait a minute.

130
00:11:12,029 --> 00:11:13,749
We're in a meeting.

131
00:11:13,749 --> 00:11:15,701
- Later.
- What's going on?

132
00:11:19,130 --> 00:11:20,901
It's the Scouting Director from Dears.

133
00:11:20,901 --> 00:11:23,495
- Hello?
- Oh, I see.

134
00:11:23,495 --> 00:11:25,548
I think I've figured it out.

135
00:11:25,548 --> 00:11:27,886
They're being scouted.

136
00:11:27,886 --> 00:11:30,226
Why hasn't anyone called me?

137
00:11:30,226 --> 00:11:31,448
Well, it means...

138
00:11:31,448 --> 00:11:32,828
You know.

139
00:11:32,828 --> 00:11:34,159
It means, what?

140
00:11:34,159 --> 00:11:36,281
I think you'd know.

141
00:11:36,281 --> 00:11:37,052
Huh?

142
00:11:37,052 --> 00:11:40,014
Now, now...

143
00:11:40,829 --> 00:11:42,745
You didn't get any calls either!

144
00:11:42,745 --> 00:11:44,565
You're no better, got that?

145
00:11:44,565 --> 00:11:47,358
As if!

146
00:11:47,358 --> 00:11:49,960
You bootlicking pipsqueak!

147
00:11:49,960 --> 00:11:51,904
You're the real pipsqueak!

148
00:11:51,904 --> 00:11:54,203
- Oh, yeah?
- Yeah, you.

149
00:11:56,214 --> 00:11:57,472
Fine, here.

150
00:11:57,472 --> 00:11:58,647
Thoughts?

151
00:11:58,647 --> 00:11:59,632
On what?

152
00:11:59,632 --> 00:12:00,959
Akito, here.

153
00:12:00,959 --> 00:12:03,946
- Please stop.
- We need your keen eye!

154
00:12:04,578 --> 00:12:05,833
It's sabermetrics.

155
00:12:05,833 --> 00:12:06,951
Don't play foul.

156
00:12:06,951 --> 00:12:08,967
You're the one playing foul!

157
00:12:08,967 --> 00:12:10,170
Kikuchi's the shorty.

158
00:12:10,170 --> 00:12:12,378
First name basis?

159
00:12:12,378 --> 00:12:14,174
- Shorty.
- Hey!

160
00:12:14,174 --> 00:12:15,890
- Get back to your seats.
- He's looking from below!

161
00:12:15,890 --> 00:12:18,012
Please just sit down.

162
00:12:18,012 --> 00:12:20,537
- We're in a meeting!
- Your personality is short.

163
00:12:20,537 --> 00:12:22,368
Back to your seats, please.

164
00:12:22,368 --> 00:12:25,474
- Yeah, back to it.
- Thanks for waiting.

165
00:12:25,474 --> 00:12:28,135
- I can't believe you all.
- Sorry, sorry.

166
00:12:28,135 --> 00:12:31,274
We were in the middle of a meeting.

167
00:12:31,952 --> 00:12:36,078
Risa Makita,
Dreams lifetime supporter, speaking.

168
00:12:36,078 --> 00:12:38,656
The Dreams will not disappear!

169
00:12:39,990 --> 00:12:42,544
Which team called?

170
00:12:42,544 --> 00:12:43,830
Prez.

171
00:12:43,830 --> 00:12:44,831
I'll take the offer...

172
00:12:44,831 --> 00:12:47,030
What?

173
00:12:47,030 --> 00:12:49,866
- Try that sentence again.
- Please, let go!

174
00:12:49,866 --> 00:12:51,111
I dare you!

175
00:12:51,111 --> 00:12:52,944
Prez!

176
00:12:54,154 --> 00:12:56,106
Ouch!

177
00:12:56,106 --> 00:12:59,436
Why is there a brawl outside the stadium?

178
00:12:59,436 --> 00:13:01,681
Get back to your seats.

179
00:13:01,681 --> 00:13:03,997
- Ow!
- You knocked us down good.

180
00:13:03,997 --> 00:13:05,548
Come on, folks.

181
00:13:05,548 --> 00:13:08,094
- Hurry!
- My neck's going to break!

182
00:13:28,967 --> 00:13:32,837
[Deposit: 500,000 Yen]

183
00:13:37,055 --> 00:13:38,319
Dad.

184
00:13:38,319 --> 00:13:42,198
Why'd you transfer the money back?

185
00:13:42,198 --> 00:13:45,413
I sent it to you, so use it.

186
00:13:45,413 --> 00:13:48,525
<i>Nah, I'm fine.</i>

187
00:13:48,525 --> 00:13:51,813
But you got hurt. Use it for the bills.

188
00:13:51,813 --> 00:13:54,235
<i>I know you've got it rough out there, too.</i>

189
00:13:54,235 --> 00:13:56,570
I'm managing just fine, Dad.

190
00:13:56,570 --> 00:14:00,340
You're always worrying about others.
This is why people exploit you.

191
00:14:01,614 --> 00:14:03,366
<i>Sorry.</i>

192
00:14:04,019 --> 00:14:05,878
You don't have to apologize.

193
00:14:05,878 --> 00:14:08,536
<i>I'm not like Mitsuo.</i>

194
00:14:08,536 --> 00:14:11,024
<i>Worrying for others is about all I can do.</i>

195
00:14:11,584 --> 00:14:14,700
Don't be so harsh on yourself.

196
00:14:25,247 --> 00:14:28,157
[Fukumoto]

197
00:14:34,650 --> 00:14:35,950
[Fukumoto]

198
00:14:41,139 --> 00:14:43,022
Why?

199
00:14:43,966 --> 00:14:47,743
I thought you'd come to regret it.

200
00:14:50,348 --> 00:14:53,155
How utterly uncalled for.

201
00:15:21,473 --> 00:15:25,481
Please give the Dreams
one more week to disband.

202
00:15:26,011 --> 00:15:29,959
What are you talking about?

203
00:15:29,959 --> 00:15:34,317
Do you realize
this is a crucial period for Yaoshima?

204
00:15:34,317 --> 00:15:36,308
Of course.

205
00:15:36,842 --> 00:15:39,088
Useless baggage should be swiftly...

206
00:15:39,088 --> 00:15:43,137
They can be sold for 10 billion yen.

207
00:15:43,784 --> 00:15:45,401
If we make capital investments,

208
00:15:45,401 --> 00:15:49,431
I believe the new business
will get on track faster.

209
00:15:50,369 --> 00:15:53,676
Will they really sell in a week?

210
00:15:55,403 --> 00:15:59,014
Sakurazaki has it covered.

211
00:15:59,014 --> 00:16:01,334
Oh my...

212
00:16:01,891 --> 00:16:07,535
You think that man can accomplish
what you failed to do so, in a week?

213
00:16:07,535 --> 00:16:09,843
He's a tough nut to crack,

214
00:16:09,843 --> 00:16:12,120
and hard to handle.

215
00:16:12,120 --> 00:16:14,480
But he is competent.

216
00:16:14,480 --> 00:16:17,083
As you know.

217
00:16:17,083 --> 00:16:21,136
Exactly. I know him.

218
00:16:21,136 --> 00:16:22,298
So?

219
00:16:22,298 --> 00:16:24,591
Is this mochi I can eat?

220
00:16:24,591 --> 00:16:26,428
Eat it, and you receive 10 billion.

221
00:16:26,428 --> 00:16:28,859
That's enough to cover
our three-year deficit.

222
00:16:28,859 --> 00:16:31,235
But if you can't, you lose nothing.

223
00:16:31,235 --> 00:16:32,805
I see.

224
00:16:32,805 --> 00:16:36,318
If you fail,

225
00:16:36,318 --> 00:16:40,039
you will follow in your father's footsteps.

226
00:16:41,226 --> 00:16:44,351
That's what trust is all about.

227
00:16:45,398 --> 00:16:48,280
I understand.

228
00:16:49,298 --> 00:16:55,333
I didn't realize
you were such a baseball fan.

229
00:17:08,841 --> 00:17:10,219
Come in.

230
00:17:11,910 --> 00:17:13,453
Excuse me.

231
00:17:14,687 --> 00:17:16,342
Have a seat.

232
00:17:24,088 --> 00:17:25,671
What did the CEO say?

233
00:17:26,944 --> 00:17:29,997
Why don't you start by thanking me?

234
00:17:30,985 --> 00:17:32,425
Thank you.

235
00:17:34,967 --> 00:17:38,583
I can practically hear the insincerity.

236
00:17:40,610 --> 00:17:42,226
I truly appreciate it.

237
00:17:42,801 --> 00:17:45,671
So, what did the CEO say?

238
00:17:49,955 --> 00:17:53,050
He will wait a week, and no longer.

239
00:17:53,050 --> 00:17:55,631
You owe me one.

240
00:17:58,421 --> 00:18:00,436
I will do what I can.

241
00:18:03,206 --> 00:18:06,807
So, who are you selling to?

242
00:18:06,807 --> 00:18:08,444
The founder of "PF".

243
00:18:09,227 --> 00:18:11,478
The communication app?

244
00:18:11,478 --> 00:18:12,659
Yes.

245
00:18:12,659 --> 00:18:17,546
I'd advise against it.
That president is a tricky one.

246
00:18:19,180 --> 00:18:21,791
He will understand our circumstances.

247
00:18:21,791 --> 00:18:25,087
I tried to sell to him before,

248
00:18:25,087 --> 00:18:27,825
but he gave me the runaround.

249
00:18:27,825 --> 00:18:32,090
He's a man I can't get a read on.

250
00:19:01,639 --> 00:19:03,835
- Mr. President.
- Yeah?

251
00:19:04,688 --> 00:19:06,060
Oh.

252
00:19:06,764 --> 00:19:08,495
They're here.

253
00:19:08,495 --> 00:19:09,756
'Sup.

254
00:19:09,756 --> 00:19:11,197
- Hello.
- Hello there.

255
00:19:11,197 --> 00:19:12,893
Have a seat.

256
00:19:12,893 --> 00:19:14,535
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

257
00:19:14,535 --> 00:19:15,828
Sure.

258
00:19:17,373 --> 00:19:19,479
When's my next meeting?

259
00:19:19,479 --> 00:19:21,751
In 47 minutes, sir.

260
00:19:21,751 --> 00:19:26,476
That's plenty for half a soccer game.

261
00:19:28,071 --> 00:19:30,523
They're here to talk baseball.

262
00:19:30,523 --> 00:19:33,170
Alright then, kick-off!

263
00:19:35,239 --> 00:19:38,658
I will get straight to the point.

264
00:19:41,767 --> 00:19:43,164
Go ahead.

265
00:19:44,195 --> 00:19:46,461
Our first condition...

266
00:19:47,226 --> 00:19:49,087
is the continued employment of our staff.

267
00:19:49,087 --> 00:19:52,545
This includes our players, coaches,
and administration.

268
00:19:52,545 --> 00:19:55,350
You're starting with that?

269
00:19:56,329 --> 00:19:58,680
I'd rather choose my own staff.

270
00:19:58,680 --> 00:20:02,467
Our staff are experts at managing the team.

271
00:20:03,474 --> 00:20:05,353
And?

272
00:20:05,353 --> 00:20:06,971
"And"?

273
00:20:07,689 --> 00:20:10,165
Come on, give it one more push.

274
00:20:10,165 --> 00:20:12,363
You gotta convince me!

275
00:20:12,363 --> 00:20:15,543
Starting a team from scratch is a huge risk.

276
00:20:15,543 --> 00:20:17,372
Mr. Sakurazaki.

277
00:20:19,686 --> 00:20:24,671
When you sell a car,
do you ask the customer how they'll use it?

278
00:20:24,671 --> 00:20:26,804
If I buy, I do what I want with the team.

279
00:20:26,804 --> 00:20:29,169
You cannot compare a car and a baseball team.

280
00:20:29,169 --> 00:20:31,666
- They're similar enough.
- What? Wait...

281
00:20:31,666 --> 00:20:35,830
You have every right to judge them
how you wish.

282
00:20:35,830 --> 00:20:38,853
However, if we keep our old staff on board,

283
00:20:38,853 --> 00:20:41,848
we can avoid the instability
often seen in newer teams.

284
00:20:43,777 --> 00:20:47,520
Play ball! Let's hear the rest.

285
00:20:47,520 --> 00:20:53,347
I also believe it's best
to keep our home base in Toyohashi.

286
00:20:53,347 --> 00:20:55,120
Relocation is a risky move.

287
00:20:55,120 --> 00:20:56,896
Right, right, right.

288
00:20:56,896 --> 00:20:58,364
Do you think otherwise?

289
00:20:58,364 --> 00:21:00,641
I do, as a matter of fact.

290
00:21:01,357 --> 00:21:02,617
Then where would we go?

291
00:21:02,617 --> 00:21:05,094
You'd come here, of course.

292
00:21:05,094 --> 00:21:07,926
To the grand ol' metropolis of Tokyo.

293
00:21:07,926 --> 00:21:10,877
Baseball teams take great pride
in the regions they represent.

294
00:21:10,877 --> 00:21:12,745
Tokyo already has their own Pelicans.

295
00:21:12,745 --> 00:21:17,057
Tokyo's got loads of people.
What's the issue in having two teams?

296
00:21:17,057 --> 00:21:20,913
Besides, there's no benefit
to staying in Toyohashi.

297
00:21:20,913 --> 00:21:22,905
President Nikaido.

298
00:21:23,656 --> 00:21:25,017
Toyohashi is your hometown, no?

299
00:21:25,017 --> 00:21:27,317
I've lived in Tokyo for half my life.

300
00:21:27,941 --> 00:21:30,889
Toyohashi's a city of my past.

301
00:21:30,889 --> 00:21:33,610
If we remain in Toyohashi,
we can use the stadium there.

302
00:21:33,610 --> 00:21:36,737
Building a new stadium elsewhere
will cost you a fortune.

303
00:21:36,737 --> 00:21:38,923
So that's your argument?

304
00:21:38,923 --> 00:21:40,216
Another counter-argument.

305
00:21:40,216 --> 00:21:42,908
Well then, how's this?

306
00:21:42,908 --> 00:21:45,019
There are many magnificent stadiums in Tokyo.

307
00:21:45,019 --> 00:21:47,769
Why not just rent them?
Wham, sound argument!

308
00:21:49,826 --> 00:21:51,725
If I may ask.

309
00:21:52,779 --> 00:21:56,887
How much did you have in mind
for the acquisition price?

310
00:21:56,887 --> 00:21:59,533
Let's see...

311
00:22:02,380 --> 00:22:04,863
President Nikaido.

312
00:22:06,820 --> 00:22:08,296
Are you even interested in buying?

313
00:22:08,296 --> 00:22:10,359
Right to it, huh?

314
00:22:12,239 --> 00:22:13,972
Honestly, no.

315
00:22:18,929 --> 00:22:22,339
I mean, you're the ones who reached out.

316
00:22:22,339 --> 00:22:25,913
Of course, I'm interested in the sports biz.

317
00:22:25,913 --> 00:22:28,320
But professional baseball?

318
00:22:28,320 --> 00:22:30,556
It's too big in many ways.

319
00:22:31,317 --> 00:22:32,417
Do you like baseball?

320
00:22:32,417 --> 00:22:35,652
Sure. But I'm no diehard fan.

321
00:22:36,336 --> 00:22:38,408
Say, I wanted to ask.

322
00:22:38,408 --> 00:22:42,361
Is Sawada's ball really that fast?

323
00:22:42,361 --> 00:22:44,406
I'd like to try hitting it once.

324
00:22:45,698 --> 00:22:46,531
What?

325
00:22:46,531 --> 00:22:48,679
I think you're underestimating baseball, sir.

326
00:22:48,679 --> 00:22:49,662
What, really?

327
00:22:49,662 --> 00:22:52,892
You'd just swing at nothing, and fall over.

328
00:22:53,581 --> 00:22:54,980
- I wouldn't.
- You would.

329
00:22:54,980 --> 00:22:57,132
- But the other day...
- Sawada is a professional.

330
00:22:58,479 --> 00:23:01,370
Did I hit a sore spot? My bad.

331
00:23:02,549 --> 00:23:07,419
I'm no baseball expert,
but I've heard about you, Mr. Sakurazaki.

332
00:23:07,419 --> 00:23:11,638
Everyone's got high praises for you.
They say you're a real wonder.

333
00:23:11,638 --> 00:23:15,127
I simply work hard. That is all.

334
00:23:15,127 --> 00:23:19,245
I hear you're a great presenter.
Why don't you try me?

335
00:23:19,245 --> 00:23:21,692
Really sell the Dreams to me.

336
00:23:21,692 --> 00:23:23,719
Of course. Shall I give it a go?

337
00:23:23,719 --> 00:23:25,972
What? Right here, right now?

338
00:23:25,972 --> 00:23:27,598
Are you sure you'll convince me?

339
00:23:27,598 --> 00:23:30,587
That depends on you, President Nikaido.

340
00:23:30,587 --> 00:23:33,026
No, it doesn't.

341
00:23:33,026 --> 00:23:37,122
A perfect presentation
would manage to convince anyone.

342
00:23:39,511 --> 00:23:42,130
Okay, let's call this halftime for now.

343
00:23:42,130 --> 00:23:45,423
I will return with a perfect presentation.

344
00:23:45,423 --> 00:23:48,167
Thank you for your valuable time today.

345
00:23:48,167 --> 00:23:49,324
We appreciate it.

346
00:23:49,324 --> 00:23:51,621
I'm looking forward to the second half.

347
00:23:51,621 --> 00:23:52,673
Thank you.

348
00:23:52,673 --> 00:23:54,118
Excuse us.

349
00:24:04,270 --> 00:24:07,637
What's with that guy? Weirdo.

350
00:24:07,637 --> 00:24:11,454
Never mind that.
We have a presentation to prepare.

351
00:24:11,454 --> 00:24:12,981
GM.

352
00:24:14,831 --> 00:24:16,703
I have a proposition.

353
00:24:17,392 --> 00:24:19,723
How about we become a civic team?

354
00:24:20,369 --> 00:24:22,070
[A team run on donations, and local support]

355
00:24:22,070 --> 00:24:25,826
Then we wouldn't be
at the mercy of a corporation.

356
00:24:29,203 --> 00:24:32,344
I strongly oppose moving to Tokyo.

357
00:24:32,344 --> 00:24:34,947
I don't want to betray our local fans.

358
00:24:38,142 --> 00:24:43,685
Is that your opinion
as President of Baseball Operations?

359
00:24:43,685 --> 00:24:45,608
- Or...
- GM.

360
00:24:46,258 --> 00:24:48,877
I love the Toyohashi Dreams.

361
00:24:57,958 --> 00:25:00,745
If we become a civic team,

362
00:25:00,745 --> 00:25:04,603
we'd have to raise
10 billion yen ourselves, right?

363
00:25:04,603 --> 00:25:06,769
Without any backing.

364
00:25:06,769 --> 00:25:09,935
We'll also need funds to keep us in business.

365
00:25:09,935 --> 00:25:16,055
Player salaries, labor costs,
and various maintenance fees add up.

366
00:25:16,055 --> 00:25:18,118
If we include these operating expenses,

367
00:25:18,118 --> 00:25:21,205
we'd need at least 15 billion yen.

368
00:25:21,205 --> 00:25:24,520
15 billion?

369
00:25:24,520 --> 00:25:26,558
That's a dizzying amount...

370
00:25:26,558 --> 00:25:29,363
Running a baseball team sure is tough.

371
00:25:29,363 --> 00:25:33,015
Why are you acting like
this isn't your problem, too?

372
00:25:37,961 --> 00:25:42,753
The Dreams have suffered
many losses until now.

373
00:25:43,770 --> 00:25:45,967
But even when we finished last,

374
00:25:46,673 --> 00:25:49,387
our fans never stopped cheering for us.

375
00:25:52,012 --> 00:25:57,150
Our athletes share their joys,
their sorrows...

376
00:25:59,370 --> 00:26:03,704
their very journeys with their fans.

377
00:26:05,895 --> 00:26:07,356
Besides,

378
00:26:08,202 --> 00:26:13,893
this year, we have amazing players
who are absolutely burning with pride.

379
00:26:17,283 --> 00:26:20,352
We can't be the ones to give up!

380
00:26:25,749 --> 00:26:27,251
President Makita.

381
00:26:28,295 --> 00:26:29,209
I'll follow you for life.

382
00:26:29,209 --> 00:26:30,429
Yeowch!

383
00:26:30,429 --> 00:26:31,845
Whoa!

384
00:26:32,757 --> 00:26:34,187
Huh?

385
00:26:34,187 --> 00:26:35,615
Alright!

386
00:26:35,615 --> 00:26:39,253
Instead of doing nothing,
let's give it a try.

387
00:26:39,253 --> 00:26:41,513
I'll set up a crowdfunding campaign.

388
00:26:41,513 --> 00:26:43,514
How about we hold a donation drive?

389
00:26:43,514 --> 00:26:46,654
I, Kikuchi, will gladly assist
in any fundraiser!

390
00:26:46,654 --> 00:26:49,800
I'll consult with local companies
who helped with ads.

391
00:26:49,800 --> 00:26:51,654
I'll reach out to local influential figures.

392
00:26:51,654 --> 00:26:55,040
Let's provide information to the media,
and get their help.

393
00:26:55,040 --> 00:26:59,831
I'll prepare materials
to present to our local government.

394
00:26:59,831 --> 00:27:01,460
Alright, everyone.

395
00:27:06,732 --> 00:27:09,042
Let us give it our all.

396
00:27:11,086 --> 00:27:13,067
Let's do this!

397
00:27:13,067 --> 00:27:16,099
Yeah!

398
00:27:16,748 --> 00:27:18,786
Dreams! Dreams!

399
00:27:18,786 --> 00:27:20,955
Dreams! Dreams!

400
00:27:20,955 --> 00:27:22,915
Dreams! Dreams!

401
00:27:22,915 --> 00:27:25,126
Dreams! Dreams!

402
00:27:25,126 --> 00:27:27,517
Dreams! Dreams!

403
00:27:27,517 --> 00:27:30,240
I apologize for making you all feel uneasy

404
00:27:30,240 --> 00:27:33,416
when it's less than a month till opening day.

405
00:27:35,528 --> 00:27:37,972
I trust you, the GM, and all the staff.

406
00:27:37,972 --> 00:27:40,258
We're with you all the way!

407
00:27:40,258 --> 00:27:41,976
Likewise, Prez.

408
00:27:41,976 --> 00:27:43,294
Me too.

409
00:27:43,294 --> 00:27:44,928
That's what we like to hear!

410
00:27:46,870 --> 00:27:51,059
Please let us help where we can.

411
00:27:51,059 --> 00:27:52,111
Isn't that right?

412
00:27:52,111 --> 00:27:53,387
Yes, sir!

413
00:27:53,387 --> 00:27:55,055
Alright, let's go!

414
00:27:56,630 --> 00:27:59,993
Thank you so much, everyone!

415
00:28:04,119 --> 00:28:05,791
Hello there!
[Please support the Dreams]

416
00:28:05,791 --> 00:28:08,097
Please lend your strength to the Dreams.
[Help the Dreams continue playing]

417
00:28:08,097 --> 00:28:10,310
Any amount will help.

418
00:28:10,310 --> 00:28:11,826
If you have a spare moment.

419
00:28:11,826 --> 00:28:13,049
We appreciate any donation.

420
00:28:13,049 --> 00:28:14,768
Even a cent would help.

421
00:28:14,768 --> 00:28:16,927
- Please.
- Anything will help.

422
00:28:16,927 --> 00:28:18,342
We'd appreciate it. Thank you.

423
00:28:18,342 --> 00:28:20,472
Please lend your strength to the Dreams.

424
00:28:20,472 --> 00:28:21,849
Please.

425
00:28:21,849 --> 00:28:23,384
- Prez!
- Please!

426
00:28:23,384 --> 00:28:26,289
We're never raising 15 billion yen
at this rate!

427
00:28:26,289 --> 00:28:28,125
Don't give up already, you idiot!

428
00:28:28,125 --> 00:28:29,076
Ouch!

429
00:28:29,076 --> 00:28:31,150
You worked your way
into the company, didn't you?

430
00:28:31,150 --> 00:28:32,197
- Ouch!
- So prove it!

431
00:28:32,197 --> 00:28:33,528
Okay, I'll do it!

432
00:28:33,528 --> 00:28:35,487
Please lend your strength to the Dreams.

433
00:28:35,487 --> 00:28:37,657
Please! Please make a donation!

434
00:28:37,657 --> 00:28:39,394
- Hello.
- Hello.

435
00:28:39,394 --> 00:28:40,895
- Good luck.
- Here.

436
00:28:40,895 --> 00:28:42,490
- Thank you.
- Huh?

437
00:28:43,377 --> 00:28:44,346
Huh?

438
00:28:44,346 --> 00:28:47,933
May the Dreams never disappear.

439
00:28:49,925 --> 00:28:51,378
Thank you.

440
00:28:54,709 --> 00:28:55,925
Miyahara!

441
00:28:55,925 --> 00:28:57,801
Mr. Kijima!

442
00:28:57,801 --> 00:28:59,995
You came!

443
00:28:59,995 --> 00:29:01,240
Thank you!

444
00:29:01,240 --> 00:29:05,329
Prez! You won't gather fans without us,
isn't that right?

445
00:29:05,329 --> 00:29:06,771
Yeah!

446
00:29:06,771 --> 00:29:08,618
Thank you all so much!

447
00:29:08,618 --> 00:29:10,356
Thank you!

448
00:29:10,356 --> 00:29:11,840
Let's do this!

449
00:29:33,114 --> 00:29:35,014
- Thank you!
- Whoa!

450
00:29:35,014 --> 00:29:38,821
Prez, we don't have enough donation boxes!

451
00:29:38,821 --> 00:29:40,214
Yeah.

452
00:29:40,214 --> 00:29:43,332
"Yeah"? What do you mean, "yeah"?

453
00:29:43,332 --> 00:29:44,868
Donations are pouring in like crazy.

454
00:29:44,868 --> 00:29:47,123
We're doing it! We can do this!

455
00:29:47,123 --> 00:29:47,977
Yeah!

456
00:29:47,977 --> 00:29:50,522
Go, go, keeping going!

457
00:29:50,522 --> 00:29:51,628
Guys!

458
00:29:51,628 --> 00:29:52,509
Osanai?

459
00:29:52,509 --> 00:29:55,045
I've secured funds
from our various fan clubs.

460
00:29:55,045 --> 00:29:56,469
It's a considerable amount when combined!

461
00:29:56,469 --> 00:29:58,294
Alright!

462
00:30:03,644 --> 00:30:08,664
The Dreams, who previously announced
their dissolution, are now a civic team.

463
00:30:08,664 --> 00:30:12,921
What a surprising turn of events.

464
00:30:12,921 --> 00:30:16,628
A team that has no company backing them

465
00:30:16,628 --> 00:30:19,260
is a first in Japanese professional baseball.

466
00:30:19,260 --> 00:30:26,515
Running a team without an owner
will be difficult, especially financially.

467
00:30:26,515 --> 00:30:30,249
<i>Still, the Dreams are known
for their strong community.</i>

468
00:30:30,249 --> 00:30:33,179
<i>I reckon the local government
will be especially supportive of them.</i>

469
00:30:36,292 --> 00:30:37,709
What?

470
00:30:40,691 --> 00:30:42,977
Weren't you going to sell the team?

471
00:30:42,977 --> 00:30:45,534
There's been a change of plans.

472
00:30:45,534 --> 00:30:46,577
Huh?

473
00:30:46,577 --> 00:30:51,021
My deal with the CEO
hinged on selling it for 10 billion yen.

474
00:30:51,021 --> 00:30:54,555
Can you keep that promise?

475
00:30:54,555 --> 00:30:58,688
Even if we raise 10 billion yen,
I can't keep my promise just yet.

476
00:30:59,708 --> 00:31:01,675
What do you mean?

477
00:31:01,675 --> 00:31:03,178
Tell me what's going on!

478
00:31:03,178 --> 00:31:07,831
The team cannot fully function
off of the 10 billion we've raised.

479
00:31:07,831 --> 00:31:09,874
How much do you need in total?

480
00:31:10,943 --> 00:31:13,019
15 billion yen.

481
00:31:16,893 --> 00:31:20,977
Where are you going to procure
the remaining 5 billion?

482
00:31:21,527 --> 00:31:25,604
I'm going to plead our case to PF once more.

483
00:31:25,604 --> 00:31:29,241
Didn't I say that man can't be convinced?

484
00:31:29,241 --> 00:31:32,379
Then I'll simply change my approach.

485
00:31:32,379 --> 00:31:34,411
Instead of having them buy us,

486
00:31:35,287 --> 00:31:37,679
I'll ask them to invest.

487
00:31:37,679 --> 00:31:42,412
Do you really think you'll convince him?

488
00:31:42,412 --> 00:31:44,579
That depends on my presentation.

489
00:31:44,579 --> 00:31:46,302
What are your odds?

490
00:31:51,354 --> 00:31:53,118
I will definitely win.

491
00:32:04,487 --> 00:32:06,957
[Mitsuo Negishi]

492
00:32:09,089 --> 00:32:10,327
Hello?

493
00:32:10,327 --> 00:32:13,697
<i>What happened to selling the team?
This isn't what we agreed on!</i>

494
00:32:14,284 --> 00:32:16,375
With all due respect, sir.

495
00:32:16,375 --> 00:32:20,087
So long as 10 billion is deposited,
I see no issue.

496
00:32:20,087 --> 00:32:22,131
<i>But how will you make that happen?</i>

497
00:32:22,131 --> 00:32:24,510
<i>Can I really count on you?</i>

498
00:32:25,943 --> 00:32:28,596
The GM says he will do it.

499
00:32:28,596 --> 00:32:32,488
I choose to believe him.

500
00:32:48,111 --> 00:32:50,426
[Pros to Investing in the Dreams]

501
00:32:50,426 --> 00:32:52,615
I would like you to invest
5 billion yen in the Dreams,

502
00:32:52,615 --> 00:32:54,508
and become our main sponsor.

503
00:32:54,508 --> 00:32:58,793
Huh? Did the game already start?

504
00:33:01,061 --> 00:33:03,575
Tell me, why should I invest?

505
00:33:03,575 --> 00:33:07,800
Because baseball as entertainment
has much to offer.

506
00:33:11,655 --> 00:33:14,340
12 teams play 143 games
in the regular season.

507
00:33:14,340 --> 00:33:19,007
Following the season,
there's the All-Star Game,

508
00:33:19,007 --> 00:33:23,233
the Climax Series, and the Japan Series.

509
00:33:23,939 --> 00:33:29,244
On average, a game brings in 30,000 people.

510
00:33:29,244 --> 00:33:32,540
What other industry
can achieve these sorts of numbers?

511
00:33:34,054 --> 00:33:37,437
Baseball sure is popular in Japan.

512
00:33:37,437 --> 00:33:39,388
Especially in the last decade.

513
00:33:39,999 --> 00:33:45,020
Half of professional baseball fans
are in their 30s and 40s.

514
00:33:45,020 --> 00:33:49,854
You can increase awareness of PF
beyond the app's younger demographic.

515
00:33:49,854 --> 00:33:51,419
And?

516
00:33:52,839 --> 00:33:58,784
By utilizing the PF app
to sell tickets, merchandise,

517
00:33:58,784 --> 00:34:01,939
and offer live streams of our games,

518
00:34:01,939 --> 00:34:04,358
you won't merely be advertising the app.

519
00:34:04,358 --> 00:34:06,925
You would be venturing
into new business opportunities.

520
00:34:06,925 --> 00:34:08,953
I see.

521
00:34:08,953 --> 00:34:12,015
That's a solid wave of attacks.

522
00:34:12,599 --> 00:34:15,700
I believe this is better than an acquisition.

523
00:34:15,700 --> 00:34:19,693
Until last year,
the Dreams were the weakest team.

524
00:34:19,693 --> 00:34:24,174
In other words, there's only up from here.

525
00:34:24,174 --> 00:34:28,121
It is an opportune time to invest.

526
00:34:30,141 --> 00:34:33,095
The Dreams will definitely get stronger.

527
00:34:33,095 --> 00:34:36,072
And that's not wishful thinking?

528
00:34:36,789 --> 00:34:40,799
Victory is entirely possible.

529
00:34:40,799 --> 00:34:44,173
The team has been in last
for two years straight.

530
00:34:44,173 --> 00:34:46,663
That's not very convincing.

531
00:34:46,663 --> 00:34:49,403
The 2021 Japan Series

532
00:34:49,403 --> 00:34:52,922
was played between teams
who finished last the year before.

533
00:34:52,922 --> 00:34:55,533
Our statement is no pipe dream.

534
00:34:57,225 --> 00:35:00,955
In addition, we're currently ranked first
in the preseason games.

535
00:35:00,955 --> 00:35:02,416
Take a look.

536
00:35:03,387 --> 00:35:05,397
[1. Dreams]

537
00:35:06,128 --> 00:35:07,704
Weak.

538
00:35:08,602 --> 00:35:10,604
Is that everything?

539
00:35:15,782 --> 00:35:19,298
Not the angle I expected you to take.

540
00:35:19,298 --> 00:35:22,006
Sounds like an interesting topic.
[What is "PF"?]

541
00:35:22,006 --> 00:35:24,711
PF is not your only success.

542
00:35:24,711 --> 00:35:28,610
You've developed many other apps
with your friends.

543
00:35:31,538 --> 00:35:34,311
You've even won numerous awards.
[Innovative Company Award]

544
00:35:37,860 --> 00:35:39,665
Not playing fair, huh?

545
00:35:39,665 --> 00:35:42,676
Though I was unaware of the origin of "PF",

546
00:35:42,676 --> 00:35:47,009
a past interview gave me the answer.

547
00:35:49,347 --> 00:35:52,732
"Playground Friends".

548
00:35:57,783 --> 00:36:02,074
These are your best friends, yes?

549
00:36:03,456 --> 00:36:07,053
As children, the three of you
always played together

550
00:36:07,053 --> 00:36:10,266
while everyone else attended cram schools.

551
00:36:12,860 --> 00:36:15,321
Where are these two individuals now?

552
00:36:23,605 --> 00:36:25,779
The three of you swore to, quote,

553
00:36:26,856 --> 00:36:29,598
"contribute the company's profits
to society".

554
00:36:29,598 --> 00:36:32,511
It was a promise you all made together.

555
00:36:32,511 --> 00:36:34,455
How is that relevant to investing?

556
00:36:34,455 --> 00:36:36,151
Easy there.

557
00:36:37,022 --> 00:36:38,978
Let's play on for now.

558
00:36:39,997 --> 00:36:44,692
You made many sacrifices
to expand your business to this extent.

559
00:36:45,557 --> 00:36:47,270
Do you remember that promise you made,

560
00:36:47,270 --> 00:36:51,957
in that cramped office, can of beer in hand?

561
00:36:55,115 --> 00:36:59,422
Now may be the time
to fulfill that very promise of yours.

562
00:36:59,422 --> 00:37:01,756
Then those two will also...

563
00:37:05,008 --> 00:37:06,289
Bravo!

564
00:37:06,966 --> 00:37:09,399
You certainly did your research.

565
00:37:09,399 --> 00:37:12,026
I had a business expert
look into the details.

566
00:37:12,026 --> 00:37:14,064
Who would bother doing that?

567
00:37:14,064 --> 00:37:17,929
You could call them
someone I can't shake off.

568
00:37:18,675 --> 00:37:20,094
Or perhaps a distant...

569
00:37:21,502 --> 00:37:23,398
yet close friend of mine.

570
00:37:32,041 --> 00:37:34,342
We were a small company back then.

571
00:37:34,974 --> 00:37:37,988
Facing fierce opposition from shareholders,

572
00:37:37,988 --> 00:37:42,492
we chose company growth
over social contribution.

573
00:37:42,492 --> 00:37:44,431
And you achieved plenty.

574
00:37:44,431 --> 00:37:45,446
That's right.

575
00:37:45,446 --> 00:37:48,556
You can't do a thing without power.

576
00:37:48,556 --> 00:37:54,289
The reason you're even asking for my help,
is because you need that power.

577
00:37:54,289 --> 00:37:59,601
I've also had my fair share
of running small teams.

578
00:37:59,601 --> 00:38:01,402
Even when we won,

579
00:38:02,255 --> 00:38:04,467
I failed to protect my colleagues.

580
00:38:04,467 --> 00:38:06,814
Isn't that because
you failed to product results?

581
00:38:06,814 --> 00:38:10,466
Maybe. Maybe not.

582
00:38:11,278 --> 00:38:16,309
Winning on its own cannot save a team.

583
00:38:21,029 --> 00:38:23,628
Grow the company.

584
00:38:23,628 --> 00:38:25,318
Produce results.

585
00:38:25,318 --> 00:38:27,837
Earn hundreds of billions of yen.

586
00:38:29,620 --> 00:38:32,266
But have you ever felt empty in your success?

587
00:38:34,846 --> 00:38:38,590
That's a pain exclusive to those who succeed.

588
00:38:38,590 --> 00:38:41,983
How can you alleviate that pain?

589
00:38:41,983 --> 00:38:43,928
I don't need to alleviate anything.

590
00:38:44,489 --> 00:38:50,334
My whole life, I had felt responsible
for protecting those around me.

591
00:38:51,733 --> 00:38:54,519
I believed it was my duty to protect them,

592
00:38:54,519 --> 00:38:56,580
and blamed myself when I failed.

593
00:38:58,116 --> 00:39:03,087
However, I'd overlooked something important.

594
00:39:07,667 --> 00:39:10,688
I wasn't the only one doing the protecting.

595
00:39:11,692 --> 00:39:16,397
I, myself, was protected
by those around me as well.

596
00:39:19,464 --> 00:39:21,883
I had teammates who respected me,

597
00:39:21,883 --> 00:39:27,804
who followed my lead
despite my stubborn ways.

598
00:39:30,281 --> 00:39:33,045
When you disagreed with your friends,

599
00:39:33,045 --> 00:39:36,497
didn't you always push your own opinion?

600
00:39:39,234 --> 00:39:41,390
So what if I did?

601
00:39:41,390 --> 00:39:45,638
Growing up alone must have felt hollow.

602
00:39:45,638 --> 00:39:48,801
You have to grow to feel empty at all.

603
00:39:49,719 --> 00:39:52,260
If I had prioritized
social contribution at the time,

604
00:39:52,260 --> 00:39:54,955
the company might have gone bankrupt.

605
00:39:56,165 --> 00:40:00,413
I chose to protect many employees
over two individuals.

606
00:40:02,272 --> 00:40:06,373
Perhaps you and I are similar.

607
00:40:07,234 --> 00:40:08,696
However...

608
00:40:10,612 --> 00:40:13,092
I now have teammates.

609
00:40:13,803 --> 00:40:16,287
And they've changed me for the better.

610
00:40:19,097 --> 00:40:21,042
I have a suggestion.

611
00:40:22,282 --> 00:40:26,970
Why don't you try changing as well?

612
00:40:26,970 --> 00:40:28,605
Me? Why?

613
00:40:28,605 --> 00:40:33,952
You would know best of all, no?

614
00:40:35,415 --> 00:40:40,243
Instead of simply chasing numbers,

615
00:40:41,426 --> 00:40:44,323
invest in a team facing dissolution.

616
00:40:45,166 --> 00:40:48,678
Become a hero who saves the 12-team system.

617
00:40:49,832 --> 00:40:52,765
If I become a hero and our profits drop,

618
00:40:52,765 --> 00:40:55,134
my employees will be out on the streets.

619
00:40:56,089 --> 00:41:00,260
A mere 5 billion yen
won't tank a company like yours.

620
00:41:00,260 --> 00:41:01,803
Besides...

621
00:41:05,399 --> 00:41:10,729
wouldn't your dear friends
be happy about this?

622
00:41:12,480 --> 00:41:15,980
Mr. Sakurazaki, your presentation
was nothing but unfair.

623
00:41:17,137 --> 00:41:20,568
It's not cool to poke at people's wounds.

624
00:41:21,714 --> 00:41:25,300
I guess you're not picky about your methods.

625
00:41:26,955 --> 00:41:29,702
Even if I were to invest,

626
00:41:30,572 --> 00:41:33,997
investing in the last-place team isn't ideal.

627
00:41:34,691 --> 00:41:37,592
We make the most popular app in the business.

628
00:41:37,592 --> 00:41:39,930
I wouldn't want to associate with the losers.

629
00:41:39,930 --> 00:41:42,977
In professional baseball,
winning and losing isn't everything.

630
00:41:44,607 --> 00:41:46,327
It has dreams.

631
00:41:48,415 --> 00:41:50,855
It has memories.

632
00:41:50,855 --> 00:41:55,750
It gives people the courage
to try again tomorrow.

633
00:41:55,750 --> 00:41:58,685
It continues to ignite the hearts of fans.

634
00:41:58,685 --> 00:42:00,466
That...

635
00:42:01,847 --> 00:42:03,886
is professional baseball.

636
00:42:06,184 --> 00:42:07,932
Please save the Dreams

637
00:42:09,514 --> 00:42:12,017
from the brink of extinction.

638
00:42:13,407 --> 00:42:19,018
Take this last-place team,
and help them become a winning one.

639
00:42:21,030 --> 00:42:24,187
Do not become a corporation
that solely pursues profit.

640
00:42:24,187 --> 00:42:26,526
Why not become a company

641
00:42:26,526 --> 00:42:29,295
that supports those who take on challenges,

642
00:42:29,295 --> 00:42:31,931
and forge new tomorrows?

643
00:42:34,480 --> 00:42:36,105
You and your friends...

644
00:42:37,294 --> 00:42:40,180
made a vow long ago.

645
00:42:42,355 --> 00:42:44,515
Now is the time to fulfill it.

646
00:42:45,551 --> 00:42:46,758
Your smooth talk won't...

647
00:42:46,758 --> 00:42:48,047
Drop it.

648
00:42:52,552 --> 00:42:55,641
Is there anything else I need to do
besides give you the money?

649
00:42:57,905 --> 00:43:02,675
Please support the Dreams.

650
00:43:13,984 --> 00:43:16,500
That reminds me.

651
00:43:18,237 --> 00:43:20,320
When I was a kid,

652
00:43:21,720 --> 00:43:24,020
I wanted to be a hero.

653
00:43:35,935 --> 00:43:37,830
Thank you.

654
00:43:38,938 --> 00:43:41,142
Thank you very much.

655
00:43:41,142 --> 00:43:44,973
However, I won't pay a single yen
over 5 billion.

656
00:43:44,973 --> 00:43:46,422
Understood.

657
00:43:47,290 --> 00:43:51,483
I have one last thing to discuss with the GM.

658
00:43:51,483 --> 00:43:53,070
Alone.

659
00:44:04,969 --> 00:44:08,192
I'll invest, on one condition.

660
00:44:10,005 --> 00:44:11,622
What is it?

661
00:44:17,364 --> 00:44:19,016
- They're here! No.
- Nope.

662
00:44:19,016 --> 00:44:20,608
- That's security.
- Right.

663
00:44:20,608 --> 00:44:22,816
Is it possible they went straight home?

664
00:44:22,816 --> 00:44:24,034
- Is it?
- Yeah.

665
00:44:24,034 --> 00:44:25,421
They never said they were dropping by.

666
00:44:25,421 --> 00:44:27,126
- Not once.
- Yeah.

667
00:44:27,816 --> 00:44:29,973
I knew it, they're...

668
00:44:29,973 --> 00:44:31,443
Woah, take your positions, people!

669
00:44:31,443 --> 00:44:32,960
They're here!

670
00:44:35,953 --> 00:44:37,573
- Huh?
- Huh?

671
00:44:40,218 --> 00:44:43,323
- Good evening.
- Evening.

672
00:44:45,850 --> 00:44:48,480
Huh? Wait, wait, wait, this is scary!

673
00:44:48,480 --> 00:44:50,373
Did they succeed? Or...

674
00:44:50,972 --> 00:44:52,804
Uh oh.

675
00:45:05,970 --> 00:45:08,563
Hooray!

676
00:45:18,148 --> 00:45:20,433
Oh! You smiled!

677
00:45:21,179 --> 00:45:22,895
Is it that unusual?

678
00:45:22,895 --> 00:45:25,390
I've never seen you smile so widely before.

679
00:45:25,390 --> 00:45:27,859
Then I'll refrain from doing so.

680
00:45:27,859 --> 00:45:29,717
Why?

681
00:45:29,717 --> 00:45:32,795
You look better with a smile.

682
00:45:37,066 --> 00:45:47,761
Dreams! Dreams!

683
00:45:51,634 --> 00:45:57,343
Why don't you celebrate with your staff?

684
00:45:57,343 --> 00:45:59,313
Feel free to praise me.

685
00:46:00,861 --> 00:46:04,610
You wouldn't want to hear praises from me.

686
00:46:04,610 --> 00:46:09,509
I only offered
because it looked as if you wanted to.

687
00:46:12,493 --> 00:46:16,518
You're still so cheeky,

688
00:46:16,518 --> 00:46:18,921
and stubborn to boot.

689
00:46:18,921 --> 00:46:21,569
How irritating indeed.

690
00:46:37,712 --> 00:46:39,487
It's delicious.

691
00:46:43,441 --> 00:46:45,506
Good work.

692
00:46:49,060 --> 00:46:51,123
Thank you very much.

693
00:47:03,268 --> 00:47:05,412
I'm home!

694
00:47:06,713 --> 00:47:09,216
I'm home!

695
00:47:09,216 --> 00:47:11,302
Welcome back!

696
00:47:11,302 --> 00:47:14,563
You're excited! Could it be?

697
00:47:14,563 --> 00:47:16,482
It worked!

698
00:47:16,482 --> 00:47:17,943
Dreams! Dreams!

699
00:47:17,943 --> 00:47:19,475
- Okay, settle down.
- Dreams! Dreams!

700
00:47:19,475 --> 00:47:21,452
Do you realize what time it is? Calm down.

701
00:47:21,452 --> 00:47:23,292
Shush... Okay?

702
00:47:25,064 --> 00:47:27,096
Here you go!

703
00:47:27,096 --> 00:47:30,021
Great call, Miyu.

704
00:47:32,174 --> 00:47:33,759
Ready?

705
00:47:33,759 --> 00:47:36,546
Cheers!

706
00:47:39,718 --> 00:47:42,049
So good!

707
00:47:43,997 --> 00:47:47,936
No binge drinking. No clinging. No whining.

708
00:47:47,936 --> 00:47:51,469
Have I made myself clear?

709
00:47:51,469 --> 00:47:55,016
Bad impression, but are you imitating the GM?

710
00:47:55,016 --> 00:47:57,590
Yeah, I copied what I saw on TV.

711
00:47:57,590 --> 00:47:59,251
Well stop, you have him all wrong.

712
00:47:59,251 --> 00:48:03,014
Oh, come on. I know you don't hate it.

713
00:48:03,014 --> 00:48:07,519
He's all you've been talking about.

714
00:48:07,519 --> 00:48:08,659
Huh?

715
00:48:08,659 --> 00:48:10,147
You didn't notice?

716
00:48:10,147 --> 00:48:11,581
- Huh?
- What?

717
00:48:12,629 --> 00:48:14,083
I have?

718
00:48:14,083 --> 00:48:16,939
She never caught on.

719
00:48:20,589 --> 00:48:21,839
Right?

720
00:48:36,576 --> 00:48:39,287
The Dreams are far from over.

721
00:48:50,733 --> 00:48:52,258
What's this?

722
00:48:53,492 --> 00:48:59,131
Before my time,
salaries used to be paid in envelopes, no?

723
00:49:00,079 --> 00:49:02,380
My father loved his job here.

724
00:49:02,380 --> 00:49:04,991
"It's Mitsuo's team", he'd say.

725
00:49:04,991 --> 00:49:09,019
He always worked with a smile on his face.

726
00:49:09,525 --> 00:49:14,224
Ridiculous. Quit harping on old memories.

727
00:49:15,985 --> 00:49:19,063
Who wants to hear that story?

728
00:49:28,202 --> 00:49:31,785
What're you doing? Stop it, that's enough!

729
00:49:31,785 --> 00:49:34,051
My father called you a great man.

730
00:49:34,051 --> 00:49:35,849
He had nothing but praise for you.

731
00:49:35,849 --> 00:49:38,393
Then one day, he came home crying,

732
00:49:38,393 --> 00:49:41,278
and said he'd quit his job here.

733
00:49:41,278 --> 00:49:43,892
Stop it! Let go of me!

734
00:49:43,892 --> 00:49:45,965
I give, I give!

735
00:49:49,631 --> 00:49:51,877
From then on, life was hell.

736
00:49:51,877 --> 00:49:55,781
Still, my father,
desperate to pay my tuition,

737
00:49:55,781 --> 00:49:58,604
knelt before you in this very room!

738
00:49:58,604 --> 00:50:02,758
To borrow money and then complain?
What a pathetic man!

739
00:50:02,758 --> 00:50:05,159
Is that how you repay a favor?

740
00:50:05,159 --> 00:50:07,424
A scumbag's son will be a scumbag himself.

741
00:50:07,424 --> 00:50:12,145
Yes, he was a kind and pathetic father.

742
00:50:12,145 --> 00:50:15,091
He wasn't particularly competent either.
However...

743
00:50:16,209 --> 00:50:17,922
he stuck to his beliefs.

744
00:50:17,922 --> 00:50:20,048
He was a proud man.

745
00:50:20,048 --> 00:50:22,793
He was nothing like you people!

746
00:50:22,793 --> 00:50:25,096
Who do you think you're talking to?

747
00:50:25,096 --> 00:50:27,857
You're fired! Get the hell out of here!

748
00:50:27,857 --> 00:50:30,297
Gladly.

749
00:50:30,297 --> 00:50:37,463
I am no longer obligated to work
with such rotten family.

750
00:50:38,202 --> 00:50:41,228
I'll pay you back with interest!

751
00:50:49,749 --> 00:50:56,370
Now I too, can stay true to my beliefs.

752
00:51:26,186 --> 00:51:28,617
- Where are you always going?
- I'm in the office sometimes.

753
00:51:28,617 --> 00:51:30,136
Whoa, careful!

754
00:51:31,011 --> 00:51:32,440
Ouch!

755
00:51:32,440 --> 00:51:34,451
What? What's wrong?

756
00:51:34,451 --> 00:51:37,262
Huh? What?

757
00:52:20,298 --> 00:52:21,962
GM!

758
00:52:27,318 --> 00:52:28,669
GM...

759
00:52:29,570 --> 00:52:31,288
You're quitting?

760
00:52:41,635 --> 00:52:46,634
Personnel reduction is necessary
for team reorganization.

761
00:52:46,634 --> 00:52:48,506
I'm no exception.

762
00:52:48,506 --> 00:52:50,957
I refuse to accept that.

763
00:52:53,529 --> 00:52:55,955
You're acting like a child.

764
00:52:55,955 --> 00:52:58,281
It's already been decided.

765
00:53:01,097 --> 00:53:05,903
I can't put any more burden
on President Nikaido.

766
00:53:06,747 --> 00:53:09,871
I'll invest, on one condition.

767
00:53:09,871 --> 00:53:11,503
Mr. Sakurazaki.

768
00:53:13,118 --> 00:53:15,957
You will resign as GM.

769
00:53:23,201 --> 00:53:25,529
Understood.

770
00:53:25,529 --> 00:53:27,544
Do you want to know why?

771
00:53:30,814 --> 00:53:34,940
Our shareholders met
to oppose this investment today.

772
00:53:35,616 --> 00:53:40,196
I'll try to convince them otherwise
the next meeting we have.

773
00:53:40,196 --> 00:53:42,274
However,

774
00:53:42,274 --> 00:53:47,292
your flashy,
and oftentimes sensational actions,

775
00:53:47,292 --> 00:53:50,167
were met with disapproval
by our conservative shareholders.

776
00:53:52,420 --> 00:53:54,797
Though I may manage to invest in the team,

777
00:53:54,797 --> 00:53:58,008
I don't have the power
to protect you as well.

778
00:54:00,031 --> 00:54:01,511
I'm used to it.

779
00:54:02,474 --> 00:54:07,499
Besides, once the season starts,
the players are the stars.

780
00:54:10,566 --> 00:54:15,934
Thanks to your decision,
I feel a little relieved.

781
00:54:16,854 --> 00:54:19,488
I would've loved to get to know you better.

782
00:54:21,303 --> 00:54:23,141
Let's grab a drink sometime, okay?

783
00:54:23,141 --> 00:54:25,199
Though I appreciate the offer,

784
00:54:25,199 --> 00:54:28,225
I'll refrain from getting any closer
than necessary.

785
00:54:33,967 --> 00:54:37,084
You really are an interesting person.

786
00:55:01,897 --> 00:55:04,124
Everyone in this city...

787
00:55:05,421 --> 00:55:07,769
loves the Dreams.

788
00:55:10,654 --> 00:55:12,924
My family was the same.

789
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:18,029
My father was especially a huge fan.

790
00:55:20,400 --> 00:55:23,065
He often took me to the dome.

791
00:55:27,426 --> 00:55:29,733
I remember a game I went to, in 5th grade.

792
00:55:32,082 --> 00:55:35,322
It was another losing match for the Dreams.

793
00:55:36,348 --> 00:55:40,076
They were down two runs against the Vikings.

794
00:55:42,201 --> 00:55:46,586
The fans were yelling to fire the manager.

795
00:55:46,586 --> 00:55:48,526
It was a huge commotion.

796
00:55:50,037 --> 00:55:51,571
That is...

797
00:55:54,054 --> 00:55:57,841
until the Dreams' cleanup hitter
hit a three-run home run.

798
00:56:00,836 --> 00:56:04,226
The fans, my dad included,
were up in arms moments before.

799
00:56:05,335 --> 00:56:07,603
But as soon as that home run was hit,

800
00:56:08,511 --> 00:56:13,107
they leapt up cheering,
with tears in their eyes.

801
00:56:14,965 --> 00:56:16,804
Grown adults, crying waterfalls.

802
00:56:21,644 --> 00:56:23,159
The next day,

803
00:56:25,531 --> 00:56:28,975
my father quit the company
he'd worked at for 20 years.

804
00:56:30,460 --> 00:56:31,912
He quit?

805
00:56:33,019 --> 00:56:35,643
He said he wanted to pursue a new dream.

806
00:56:42,385 --> 00:56:44,182
That home run...

807
00:56:45,237 --> 00:56:47,260
must have given him courage.

808
00:56:48,424 --> 00:56:49,991
Yes.

809
00:56:52,010 --> 00:56:56,986
Like us, there are many people
who are encouraged by the Dreams,

810
00:56:57,960 --> 00:57:02,368
and overcome their tough daily lives.

811
00:57:05,129 --> 00:57:08,040
GM, you protected that place for everyone.

812
00:57:13,637 --> 00:57:16,624
Are you really going to quit?

813
00:57:16,624 --> 00:57:18,842
Is there nothing that can be done?

814
00:57:22,015 --> 00:57:24,514
I don't want you to go.

815
00:57:27,026 --> 00:57:28,980
You protected the Dreams.

816
00:57:28,980 --> 00:57:30,504
The fans.

817
00:57:31,287 --> 00:57:32,889
The entire staff.

818
00:57:35,042 --> 00:57:37,761
You protected us all.

819
00:57:40,965 --> 00:57:43,917
There's still so much
we want to learn from you.

820
00:57:46,000 --> 00:57:51,287
You'll all be fine without me.

821
00:57:52,576 --> 00:57:56,768
Besides, I'm used to being alone.

822
00:57:57,444 --> 00:57:59,774
And to leaving.

823
00:58:04,494 --> 00:58:05,923
GM...

824
00:58:07,052 --> 00:58:09,809
No one was able to protect you again.

825
00:58:11,891 --> 00:58:13,880
That's not true.

826
00:58:14,814 --> 00:58:16,874
You...

827
00:58:22,144 --> 00:58:24,073
You all protected me.

828
00:58:25,518 --> 00:58:27,527
That's why I'm here now.

829
00:58:29,399 --> 00:58:31,072
Besides...

830
00:58:33,510 --> 00:58:38,810
For me, this is the first place
I've ever truly protected.

831
00:58:41,659 --> 00:58:43,426
That alone...

832
00:58:50,828 --> 00:58:53,036
That alone is enough.

833
00:58:56,575 --> 00:58:58,316
I wish we could have...

834
00:59:25,477 --> 00:59:28,589
[Regular Season Final Game]

835
00:59:28,589 --> 00:59:32,227
[October 5th]

836
00:59:45,343 --> 00:59:48,050
Morning!

837
00:59:51,558 --> 00:59:56,263
Hey, hey, what's wrong?
You boys getting nervous?

838
00:59:56,263 --> 00:59:58,018
Hey, you're stiff!

839
00:59:58,018 --> 00:59:59,967
Says you!

840
00:59:59,967 --> 01:00:03,700
Let's win this season,
and give Kijima a grand send-off.

841
01:00:04,423 --> 01:00:05,502
Hey, Manager!

842
01:00:05,502 --> 01:00:07,062
I'm not retiring yet!

843
01:00:07,062 --> 01:00:09,088
- We'll miss you!
- Hey, quit it!

844
01:00:09,088 --> 01:00:10,064
[Yuki Kijima]

845
01:00:10,064 --> 01:00:13,676
[9 Holds, 30 Saves, 1.60 ERA]

846
01:00:13,676 --> 01:00:15,840
Sawada, how are you feeling?

847
01:00:15,840 --> 01:00:17,454
I'm in top form!

848
01:00:18,207 --> 01:00:19,641
We're counting on you today!

849
01:00:19,641 --> 01:00:21,632
Yes, sir!

850
01:00:21,632 --> 01:00:22,576
[Takeru Sawada]

851
01:00:22,576 --> 01:00:25,813
[15 Wins, 3 Losses]
[154 Strikeouts, 1.69 ERA]

852
01:00:25,813 --> 01:00:29,497
I'll lead the way, so leave it to me.

853
01:00:29,497 --> 01:00:31,172
Did your hemorrhoids heal?

854
01:00:31,172 --> 01:00:32,177
Shush!

855
01:00:32,177 --> 01:00:33,101
[Takashi Iwata]

856
01:00:33,101 --> 01:00:37,074
[.264 Batting Average, 62 RBIs]
[.458 Caught Stealing Percentage]

857
01:00:37,074 --> 01:00:38,528
- Hey, Kudo.
- Yes?

858
01:00:38,528 --> 01:00:41,554
Your fan got so rowdy they were escorted out.

859
01:00:41,554 --> 01:00:45,660
He got caught, again? That drunkard!

860
01:00:45,660 --> 01:00:48,035
They love you!

861
01:00:48,685 --> 01:00:49,628
[Tatsuya Kudo]

862
01:00:49,628 --> 01:00:53,383
[.316 Batting Average, 22 RBIs, 9 Home Runs]

863
01:00:53,383 --> 01:00:55,155
- Yuto.
- Yes, sir.

864
01:00:55,155 --> 01:00:56,553
Stir things up again, you hear?

865
01:00:56,553 --> 01:00:58,282
Lead-off batter!

866
01:00:58,282 --> 01:01:00,362
Leave it to me!

867
01:01:00,362 --> 01:01:01,290
I'll show them what's up!

868
01:01:01,290 --> 01:01:02,207
[Yuto Nara]

869
01:01:02,207 --> 01:01:05,932
[.328 Batting Average, 34 Stolen Bases]
[.396 On-base Percentage]

870
01:01:08,385 --> 01:01:11,193
I'm sorry I'm late.

871
01:01:11,193 --> 01:01:13,077
Hey, where were you?

872
01:01:13,077 --> 01:01:17,094
The game is being broadcasted live in Korea.

873
01:01:17,094 --> 01:01:19,676
I was calling my grandma.

874
01:01:21,401 --> 01:01:22,452
[Lim Min Jong]

875
01:01:22,452 --> 01:01:25,857
[10 Wins, 4 Losses, 96 Strikeouts, 2.31 ERA]

876
01:01:25,857 --> 01:01:28,126
Hello there, team.

877
01:01:28,126 --> 01:01:30,563
Morning, Prez.

878
01:01:32,454 --> 01:01:35,580
If we win today, we'll be league champions
for the first time in 14 years!

879
01:01:35,580 --> 01:01:36,833
Let's give it all we've got!

880
01:01:36,833 --> 01:01:38,552
Yeah!

881
01:01:38,552 --> 01:01:42,140
We'll win the league,
and take the Japan Series too!

882
01:01:42,140 --> 01:01:44,302
Yeah!

883
01:01:44,302 --> 01:01:47,478
Who's the only team
that's ahead on wins against the Vikings?

884
01:01:47,478 --> 01:01:48,813
The Dreams!

885
01:01:48,813 --> 01:01:50,881
Alright everyone, let's crush them!

886
01:01:50,881 --> 01:01:53,326
Hell yeah!

887
01:01:53,326 --> 01:02:00,001
Dreams! Dreams!

888
01:02:00,001 --> 01:02:02,492
Alright, let's do this!

889
01:02:09,808 --> 01:02:12,170
Today is just a stepping stone.

890
01:02:12,170 --> 01:02:13,488
Go out there, and win!

891
01:02:13,488 --> 01:02:15,932
Yeah!

892
01:02:21,985 --> 01:02:23,941
Mr. Kijima.

893
01:02:23,941 --> 01:02:25,873
Miyahara.

894
01:02:27,767 --> 01:02:29,143
Thanks.

895
01:02:29,143 --> 01:02:31,491
Thank you.

896
01:02:31,491 --> 01:02:33,183
Hey, don't cry!

897
01:02:33,183 --> 01:02:35,029
It's before the game!

898
01:02:35,029 --> 01:02:36,451
I'm sorry.

899
01:03:41,727 --> 01:03:45,262
[1056 AM Tokai]

900
01:03:45,262 --> 01:03:48,341
It's the final game of the season,
with a 0.5 game difference.

901
01:03:48,341 --> 01:03:51,327
The winning team
will be our league champions.

902
01:03:51,953 --> 01:03:54,460
Will the Dreams emerge victorious?

903
01:03:54,460 --> 01:03:57,023
Or will it be the Vikings?

904
01:03:57,023 --> 01:04:00,108
Kudo! Kudo! Kudo!

905
01:04:00,108 --> 01:04:02,554
Bottom of the 8th.
Onizuka is on the mound.

906
01:04:02,554 --> 01:04:05,223
Kudo, the cleanup hitter, is at bat.

907
01:04:06,059 --> 01:04:07,801
He got it!

908
01:04:07,801 --> 01:04:09,659
The ball is in left-center!

909
01:04:09,659 --> 01:04:11,813
It's going! It's going!

910
01:04:11,813 --> 01:04:14,620
And it's outta here!

911
01:04:14,620 --> 01:04:17,592
The Dreams are ever closer to victory!

912
01:04:17,592 --> 01:04:21,119
<i>Tatsuya Kudo's hit a game-changing homer!</i>

913
01:04:36,570 --> 01:04:40,132
One more out! One more out!

914
01:04:48,342 --> 01:04:51,724
One more out! One more out!

915
01:04:51,724 --> 01:04:54,791
One more out! One more out!

916
01:04:54,791 --> 01:04:57,132
The Dreams, after years
of being at the bottom,

917
01:04:57,132 --> 01:04:59,566
are cheered on by their long-suffering fans!

918
01:04:59,566 --> 01:05:04,148
Only one out left
until their first league win in 14 years!

919
01:05:06,918 --> 01:05:08,571
One more out!

920
01:05:08,571 --> 01:05:10,030
- One more out!
- Mr. Kijima...

921
01:05:10,030 --> 01:05:12,186
Mr. Kijima, please...

922
01:05:12,186 --> 01:05:14,342
- One more out!
- Mr. Kijima...

923
01:06:24,451 --> 01:06:27,907
I've been waiting for you.

924
01:06:28,984 --> 01:06:31,221
Allow me to guess.

925
01:06:31,221 --> 01:06:33,187
Did you stop by the Dreams game?

926
01:06:37,004 --> 01:06:38,693
What did you want?

927
01:06:41,136 --> 01:06:45,466
You're still a tough nut to crack.

928
01:06:48,942 --> 01:06:52,824
There's a team that's interested in you.

929
01:06:55,477 --> 01:07:01,533
Like the Dreams,
they're a pitifully weak team.

930
01:07:04,037 --> 01:07:05,676
That's fine by me.

931
01:07:08,011 --> 01:07:10,491
I'll make sure they win.

932
01:07:15,694 --> 01:07:18,006
Another baseball team?

933
01:07:18,006 --> 01:07:21,335
No! It's "baseball"!

934
01:07:23,496 --> 01:07:27,850
Triple-A. They're minor leaguers.

935
01:07:28,768 --> 01:07:30,578
The States?

936
01:07:32,890 --> 01:07:35,115
Feel free to despise me all you wish,

937
01:07:35,115 --> 01:07:38,494
even from across the ocean.

938
01:07:43,704 --> 01:07:45,359
I'm sorry!

939
01:07:51,537 --> 01:07:52,984
Ready?

940
01:08:02,552 --> 01:08:04,303
Thank you!

941
01:08:07,344 --> 01:08:10,348
I thought you never played.

942
01:08:13,720 --> 01:08:18,216
Since we're here,
why don't we have a celebratory drink?

943
01:08:20,339 --> 01:08:21,856
No, thank you.

